E2E test runner already added (from `write-tests` command)\\n     9→- If neither exists, read the agent's docs and ask the user about hook events, transcript format, and config\\n    10→\\n    11→## Procedure\\n    12→\\n    13→### Step 1: Read Implementation Guide\\n    14→\\n    15→Read these files thoroughly before writing any code:\\n    16→\\n    17→1. `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Authoritative implementation guide with code templates. Read thoroughly.\\n    18→2. `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Validation criteria for completeness.\\n    19→3. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` — Read to find the exact `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces.\\n    20→4. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read to find `EventType` constants and shared parsing helpers.\\n    21→\\n    22→### Step 2: Read Reference Implementation\\n    23→\\n    24→Run `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Pick the closest match based on research findings — read a few agents' `hooks.go` files to find one with a similar hook mechanism to your target. Read all `*.go` files (skip `*_test.go` on first pass) in the chosen reference.\\n    25→\\n    26→### Step 3: Create Bare-Minimum Compiling Package\\n    27→\\n    28→Create the agent package directory and stub out every required interface method so the project compiles.\\n    29→\\n    30→```\\n    31→cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG/\\n    32→```\\n    33→\\n    34→**What to create:**\\n    35→\\n    36→1. **`${AGENT_SLUG}.go`** — Struct definition, `init()` with `agent.Register(agent.AgentName(\\\"$AGENT_SLUG\\\"), New)`, and stub implementations for all `Agent` interface methods (Name, Type, Description, IsPreview, DetectPresence, ProtectedDirs, GetSessionDir, ResolveSessionFile, ReadTranscript, ChunkTranscript, ReassembleTranscript).\\n    37→2. **`types.go`** — Hook input struct(s) with JSON tags matching the research captures.\\n    38→3. **`lifecycle.go`** — Stub `ParseHookEvent()` that returns `nil, nil` for all inputs.\\n    39→4. **`hooks.go`** — Stub `InstallHooks()`, `UninstallHooks()`, `AreHooksInstalled()` that return nil/false.\\n    40→5. **`transcript.go`** — Stub `TranscriptAnalyzer` methods if the research report says the agent supports transcript analysis.\\n    41→\\n    42→**Wire up blank imports:**\\n    43→\\n    44→- Add `_ \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG\\\"` to `cmd/entire/cli/agent/hooks_cmd.go`\\n    45→- Add the agent to the config map in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/config.go`\\n    46→\\n    47→**Verify compilation:**\\n    48→\\n    49→```bash\\n    50→mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test\\n    51→```\\n    52→\\n    53→Everything must pass before proceeding. Fix any issues.\\n    54→\\n    55→### Step 4: E2E Tier 1 — `TestHumanOnlyChangesAndCommits`\\n    56→\\n    57→This test requires no agent prompts — it only exercises hooks, so it's the fastest feedback loop.\\n    58→\\n    59→**What it exercises:**\\n    60→- `InstallHooks()` — real hook installation in the agent's config\\n    61→- `AreHooksInstalled()` — detection that hooks are present\\n    62→- `ParseHookEvent()` — at minimum, the `SessionStart` and `Stop` event types\\n    63→- Basic hook invocation flow (the test calls hooks directly via the CLI)\\n    64→\\n    65→**Cycle:**\\n    66→\\n    67→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestHumanOnlyChangesAndCommits`\\n    68→2. Read the failure output carefully\\n    69→3. If there are artifact dirs, use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` to understand what happened\\n    70→4. Implement the minimum code to fix the first failure\\n    71→5. Repeat until the test passes\\n    72→\\n    73→**After passing, write unit tests:**\\n    74→\\n    75→- `hooks_test.go` — Test `InstallHooks` (creates config, idempotent), `UninstallHooks` (removes hooks), `AreHooksInstalled` (detects presence). Use a temp directory to avoid touching real config.\\n    76→- `lifecycle_test.go` (initial) — Test `ParseHookEvent` for the event types exercised so far (`SessionStart`, `Stop`). Include nil return for unknown hook names and malformed JSON input.\\n    77→\\n    78→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n    79→\\n    80→### Step 5: E2E Tier 2 — `TestSingleSessionManualCommit`\\n    81→\\n    82→The foundational test. This exercises the full agent lifecycle: start session → agent prompt → agent produces files → user commits → session ends.\\n    83→\\n    84→**What it exercises:**\\n    85→- Complete `ParseHookEvent()` for all 4 basic events: `SessionStart`, `UserPromptSubmit`, `SubagentTaskStart`/`SubagentTaskEnd` (if applicable), `Stop`\\n    86→- `GetSessionDir` / `ResolveSessionFile` — finding the agent's session/transcript files\\n    87→- `ReadTranscript` / `ChunkTranscript` / `ReassembleTranscript` — reading native transcript format\\n    88→- `TranscriptAnalyzer` methods: `ExtractFilesTouched`, `ExtractUserPrompts`, `GenerateContext`\\n    89→\\n    90→**Cycle:**\\n    91→\\n    92→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestSingleSessionManualCommit`\\n    93→2. Read the failure output carefully\\n    94→3. Use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` to understand what happened\\n    95→4. Implement the minimum code to fix the first failure\\n    96→5. Repeat until the test passes\\n    97→\\n    98→**After passing, write unit tests:**\\n    99→\\n   100→- `types_test.go` — Test hook input struct parsing with actual JSON payloads from research captures.\\n   101→- `lifecycle_test.go` (complete) — Test `ParseHookEvent` for all 4 event types. Use actual JSON payloads. Test every `EventType` mapping, nil returns for pass-through hooks, empty input, and malformed JSON.\\n   102→- `transcript_test.go` — Test `ReadTranscript`, `ChunkTranscript`, `ReassembleTranscript` with sample data in the agent's native format. Test `ExtractFilesTouched`, `ExtractUserPrompts`, `GenerateContext` if `TranscriptAnalyzer` is implemented.\\n   103→\\n   104→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   105→\\n   106→### Step 6: E2E Tier 2b — `TestCheckpointMetadataDeepValidation`\\n   107→\\n   108→Validates transcript quality: JSONL validity, content hash correctness, prompt extraction accuracy.\\n   109→\\n   110→**What it exercises:**\\n   111→- Transcript content stored at checkpoints is valid JSONL\\n   112→- Content hash matches the stored transcript\\n   113→- User prompts are correctly extracted\\n   114→- Metadata fields are populated\\n   115→\\n   116→**Cycle:**\\n   117→\\n   118→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestCheckpointMetadataDeepValidation`\\n   119→2. Use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` on any failures — this test often exposes subtle transcript formatting bugs\\n   120→3. Fix and repeat\\n   121→\\n   122→**After passing:** Update `transcript_test.go` if any edge cases were discovered.\\n   123→\\n   124→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   125→\\n   126→### Step 7: E2E Tier 3 — `TestSingleSessionAgentCommitInTurn`\\n   127→\\n   128→Agent creates files and commits them within a single prompt turn. Tests the in-turn commit path.\\n   129→\\n   130→**What it exercises:**\\n   131→- Hook events firing during an agent's commit (post-commit hooks while agent is active)\\n   132→- Checkpoint creation when agent commits mid-turn\\n   133→- Usually no new agent-specific code needed — this tests the strategy's handling of agent commits\\n   134→\\n   135→**Cycle:**\\n   136→\\n   137→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestSingleSessionAgentCommitInTurn`\\n   138→2. Use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` on failures\\n   139→3. Fix and repeat — if the agent doesn't support committing, skip this test\\n   140→\\n   141→**After passing:** Add any new edge cases to existing unit tests if bugs were found.\\n   142→\\n   143→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   144→\\n   145→### Step 8: E2E Tier 4 — Multi-Session Tests\\n   146→\\n   147→Run these tests to validate multi-session behavior:\\n   148→\\n   149→- `TestMultiSessionManualCommit` — Two sessions, both produce files, user commits\\n   150→- `TestMultiSessionSequential` — Sessions run one after another\\n   151→- `TestEndedSessionUserCommitsAfterExit` — User commits after session ends\\n   152→\\n   153→**Cycle (for each test):**\\n   154→\\n   155→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestMultiSessionManualCommit`\\n   156→2. Use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` on failures\\n   157→3. Fix and repeat\\n   158→4. Move to next test\\n   159→\\n   160→**After all pass:** These tests rarely need new agent code — they exercise the strategy layer. Update unit tests only if agent-specific bugs were found.\\n   161→\\n   162→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   163→\\n   164→### Step 9: E2E Tier 5 — File Operation Edge Cases\\n   165→\\n   166→Run these tests for file operation correctness:\\n   167→\\n   168→- `TestModifyExistingTrackedFile` — Agent modifies (not creates) a file\\n   169→- `TestUserSplitsAgentChanges` — User stages only some of the agent's changes\\n   170→- `TestDeletedFilesCommitDeletion` — Agent deletes a file, user commits the deletion\\n   171→- `TestMixedNewAndModifiedFiles` — Agent both creates and modifies files\\n   172→\\n   173→**Cycle:** Same as above — run each test, use `/debug-e2e` on failures, fix, repeat.\\n   174→\\n   175→**After all pass:** Update unit tests if any transcript parsing or file-touched extraction bugs were discovered.\\n   176→\\n   177→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   178→\\n   179→### Step 10: Optional Interfaces\\n   180→\\n   181→Read `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` for all optional interfaces. For each one the research report marked as feasible:\\n   182→\\n   183→- **`TranscriptPreparer`** — If the agent needs pre-processing before transcript storage\\n   184→- **`TokenCalculator`** — If the agent provides token usage data\\n   185→- **`SubagentAwareExtractor`** — If the agent has subagent/tool-use patterns\\n   186→\\n   187→For each optional interface:\\n   188→\\n   189→1. Implement the methods based on research findings\\n   190→2. Write unit tests for the new methods\\n   191→3. Run relevant E2E tests to verify integration\\n   192→\\n   193→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   194→\\n   195→### Step 11: E2E Tier 6 — Interactive and Rewind Tests\\n   196→\\n   197→Run these if the agent supports interactive multi-step sessions:\\n   198→\\n   199→- `TestInteractiveMultiStep` — Multiple prompts in one session\\n   200→- `TestRewindPreCommit` — Rewind to a checkpoint before committing\\n   201→- `TestRewindAfterCommit` — Rewind to a checkpoint after committing\\n   202→- `TestRewindMultipleFiles` — Rewind with multiple files changed\\n   203→\\n   204→**Cycle:** Same pattern — run, `/debug-e2e` on failures, fix, repeat.\\n   205→\\n   206→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   207→\\n   208→### Step 12: E2E Tier 7 — Complex Scenarios\\n   209→\\n   210→Run the remaining edge case and stress tests:\\n   211→\\n   212→- `TestPartialCommitStashNewPrompt` — Partial commit, stash, new prompt\\n   213→- `TestStashSecondPromptUnstashCommitAll` — Stash workflow across prompts\\n   214→- `TestRapidSequentialCommits` — Multiple commits in quick succession\\n   215→- `TestAgentContinuesAfterCommit` — Agent keeps working after a commit\\n   216→- `TestSubagentCommitFlow` — If the agent has subagent support\\n   217→- `TestSingleSessionSubagentCommitInTurn` — Subagent commits during a turn\\n   218→\\n   219→**Cycle:** Same pattern. Many of these require no new agent code — they exercise strategy-layer behavior.\\n   220→\\n   221→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test`\\n   222→\\n   223→### Step 13: Register and Wire Up\\n   224→\\n   225→1. **Register hook commands**: Search `cmd/entire/cli/` for where hook subcommands are registered and add the new agent\\n   226→2. **Verify registration**: The `init()` function in `${AGENT_SLUG}.go` should call `agent.Register(agent.AgentName(\\\"$AGENT_SLUG\\\"), New)`\\n   227→3. **Run full test suite**: `mise run test:ci`\\n   228→\\n   229→### Step 14: Final Validation\\n   230→\\n   231→Run the complete validation:\\n   232→\\n   233→```bash\\n   234→mise run fmt      # Format\\n   235→mise run lint     # Lint\\n   236→mise run test:ci  # All tests (unit + integration)\\n   237→```\\n   238→\\n   239→Check against the integration checklist (`docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md`):\\n   240→\\n   241→- [ ] Full transcript stored at every checkpoint\\n   242→- [ ] Native format preserved\\n   243→- [ ] All mappable hook events implemented\\n   244→- [ ] Session storage working\\n   245→- [ ] Hook installation/uninstallation working\\n   246→- [ ] Tests pass with `t.Parallel()`\\n   247→\\n   248→## E2E Debugging Protocol\\n   249→\\n   250→At every E2E failure, follow this protocol:\\n   251→\\n   252→1. **Read the test output** — the assertion message often tells you exactly what's wrong\\n   253→2. **Find the artifact directory** — E2E tests save artifacts (logs, transcripts, git state) to a temp dir printed in the output\\n   254→3. **Run `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}`** — this skill analyzes artifacts and diagnoses the root cause\\n   255→4. **Implement the minimum fix** — don't over-engineer; fix only what the test demands\\n   256→5. **Re-run the failing test** — not the whole suite, just the one test\\n   257→\\n   258→## Key Patterns to Follow\\n   259→\\n   260→- **Use `agent.ReadAndParseHookInput[T]`** for parsing hook stdin JSON\\n   261→- **Use `paths.WorktreeRoot()`** not `os.Getwd()` for git-relative paths\\n   262→- **Preserve unknown config keys** when modifying agent config files (don't clobber user settings)\\n   263→- **Use `logging.Debug/Info/Warn/Error`** for internal logging, not `fmt.Print`\\n   264→- **Keep interface implementations minimal** — only implement what's needed\\n