oding agent's hook/lifecycle model is compatible with the Entire CLI before writing any Go code.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Procedure\\n     6→\\n     7→### Phase 1: Understand Entire's Expectations\\n     8→\\n     9→Read `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` to understand what Entire expects from agents: EventType names, required interfaces, hook patterns, and lifecycle flow. This gives you the vocabulary to map the target agent's native hooks to Entire's event model.\\n    10→\\n    11→**Do NOT read other internal Entire source files** (`agent.go`, `event.go`, `hook_registry.go`, `lifecycle.go`, checklist, or reference implementations). The implementer handles those.\\n    12→\\n    13→### Phase 2: Static Capability Checks\\n    14→\\n    15→Non-destructive CLI probing. Record PASS/WARN/FAIL for each:\\n    16→\\n    17→| Check | Command | PASS | FAIL |\\n    18→|-------|---------|------|------|\\n    19→| Binary present | `command -v $AGENT_BIN` | Found | Not found (blocker) |\\n    20→| Help output | `$AGENT_BIN --help` or `$AGENT_BIN help` | Available | No help |\\n    21→| Version info | `$AGENT_BIN --version` or `$AGENT_BIN version` | Available | N/A |\\n    22→| Hook keywords | Scan help for: hook, lifecycle, callback, event, trigger, pre-, post-, plugin, extension | Found | None found |\\n    23→| Session keywords | Scan help for: session, resume, continue, history, transcript, context | Found | None found |\\n    24→| Config directory | Check `~/.$AGENT_SLUG/`, `~/.config/$AGENT_SLUG/`, `./$AGENT_SLUG/`, `./.${AGENT_SLUG}/` | Found | None found |\\n    25→| Documentation | Web search for hook/plugin/extension docs | Found | None found |\\n    26→\\n    27→### Phase 3: Test Script Creation\\n    28→\\n    29→Based on Phase 2 findings, create an **agent-specific** test script:\\n    30→\\n    31→```\\n    32→scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh\\n    33→```\\n    34→\\n    35→The script is tailored to the specific agent's hook mechanism (not a generic template). Adapt the hook wiring section based on what Phase 2 discovered.\\n    36→\\n    37→**Script structure:**\\n    38→\\n    39→```bash\\n    40→#!/usr/bin/env bash\\n    41→set -euo pipefail\\n    42→\\n    43→AGENT_NAME=\\\"...\\\"\\n    44→AGENT_SLUG=\\\"...\\\"\\n    45→AGENT_BIN=\\\"...\\\"\\n    46→PROBE_DIR=\\\".entire/tmp/probe-${AGENT_SLUG}-$(date +%s)\\\"\\n    47→```\\n    48→\\n    49→**Required sections:**\\n    50→\\n    51→1. **Static checks** — Re-runnable binary/version/help checks\\n    52→2. **Hook wiring** — Create workspace-local config that intercepts hooks and dumps stdin JSON to `$PROBE_DIR/captures/<event-name>-<timestamp>.json`\\n    53→3. **Run modes:**\\n    54→   - `--run-cmd '<cmd>'` — Automated: launch agent, wait, collect\\n    55→   - `--manual-live` — Interactive: user runs agent manually, presses Enter\\n    56→4. **Capture collection** — List and pretty-print all payload files\\n    57→5. **Cleanup** — Restore original config (unless `--keep-config`)\\n    58→6. **Verdict** — PASS/WARN/FAIL per lifecycle event + COMPATIBLE/PARTIAL/INCOMPATIBLE\\n    59→\\n    60→### Phase 4: Execution & Analysis\\n    61→\\n    62→Run the script and analyze:\\n    63→\\n    64→1. **Execute**: `chmod +x scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh && scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh --manual-live`\\n    65→2. **For each captured payload**: show command, artifact path, decoded JSON\\n    66→3. **Lifecycle mapping**: native hook name → Entire EventType\\n    67→4. **Field coverage**: which `Event` struct fields can be populated per event\\n    68→\\n    69→### Phase 5: Implementation One-Pager\\n    70→\\n    71→Write the research findings to `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG/AGENT.md` as a structured one-pager that the test-writer and implementer phases will use as their single source of agent-specific information.\\n    72→\\n    73→**Create the agent package directory first** (if it doesn't exist):\\n    74→\\n    75→```bash\\n    76→mkdir -p cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG\\n    77→```\\n    78→\\n    79→**Write the one-pager using this template:**\\n    80→\\n    81→```markdown\\n    82→# $AGENT_NAME — Integration One-Pager\\n    83→\\n    84→## Verdict: COMPATIBLE / PARTIAL / INCOMPATIBLE\\n    85→\\n    86→## Binary\\n    87→- Name: `$AGENT_BIN`\\n    88→- Version: ...\\n    89→- Install: ... (how to install if not present)\\n    90→\\n    91→## Hook Mechanism\\n    92→- Config file: `~/.config/$AGENT_SLUG/settings.json` (exact path)\\n    93→- Config format: JSON / YAML / TOML\\n    94→- Hook registration: ... (how hooks are declared — JSON objects, env vars, etc.)\\n    95→- Hook names and when they fire:\\n    96→  | Native Hook Name | When It Fires | Entire EventType |\\n    97→  |-----------------|---------------|-----------------|\\n    98→  | `on_session_start` | Agent session begins | `SessionStart` |\\n    99→  | ... | ... | ... |\\n   100→- Hook input (stdin JSON): ... (exact fields with example payload)\\n   101→\\n   102→## Transcript\\n   103→- Location: `~/.config/$AGENT_SLUG/sessions/<id>/transcript.jsonl`\\n   104→- Format: JSONL / JSON array / other\\n   105→- Session ID extraction: ... (from hook payload field or directory name)\\n   106→- Example entry: `{\\\"role\\\": \\\"user\\\", \\\"content\\\": \\\"...\\\"}`\\n   107→\\n   108→## Config Preservation\\n   109→- Keys to preserve when modifying: ... (or \\\"use read-modify-write on entire file\\\")\\n   110→- Settings that affect hook behavior: ...\\n   111→\\n   112→## CLI Flags\\n   113→- Non-interactive prompt: `$AGENT_BIN --prompt \\\"...\\\" --no-confirm`\\n   114→- Interactive mode: `$AGENT_BIN` (or \\\"not supported\\\")\\n   115→- Relevant env vars: ...\\n   116→\\n   117→## Gaps & Limitations\\n   118→- ... (anything that doesn't map cleanly)\\n   119→\\n   120→## Captured Payloads\\n   121→- See `.entire/tmp/probe-$AGENT_SLUG-*/captures/` for raw JSON captures\\n   122→```\\n   123→\\n   124→**Key points about the one-pager:**\\n   125→\\n   126→- The **Entire EventType mapping** (which native hook → which EventType) uses the event names learned from `agent-guide.md` in Phase 1. The researcher can do this mapping because it's a simple table — it doesn't need Entire source code.\\n   127→- Fill in every section with concrete values from Phases 2-4. Don't leave placeholders.\\n   128→- If a section doesn't apply (e.g., no transcript support), say so explicitly.\\n   129→- This file persists as development documentation — future maintainers will reference it.\\n   130→\\n   131→## Blocker Handling\\n   132→\\n   133→If blocked at any point (auth, sandbox, binary not found):\\n   134→\\n   135→1. State the exact blocker\\n   136→2. Provide the exact command for the user to run manually\\n   137→3. Explain what output to paste back\\n   138→4. Continue with provided output\\n   139→\\n   140→## Constraints\\n   141→\\n   142→- **No Go code.** This command produces a one-pager and test script only.\\n   143→- **Non-destructive.** All artifacts go under `.entire/tmp/` (gitignored). The one-pager goes in the agent package directory.\\n   144→- **Agent-specific scripts.** Adapt based on Phase 2 findings, not a generic template.\\n   145→- **Ask, don't assume.** If the hook mechanism is unclear, ask the user.\\n   146→- **External focus.** Do not read internal Entire source files beyond `agent-guide.md`. The implementer reads those.\\n   147→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"c0fb4f59-3c83-43f7-bc62-b9629eb4b7d4\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T01:03:22.905Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot/.claude/skills/agent-integration/researcher.md\",\"content\":\"# Research Command\\n\\nAssess whether a target AI coding agent's hook/lifecycle model is compatible with the Entire CLI before writing any Go code.\\n\\n## Procedure\\n\\n### Phase 1: Understand Entire's Expectations\\n\\nRead `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` to understand what Entire expects from agents: EventType names, required interfaces, hook patterns, and lifecycle flow. This gives you the vocabulary to map the target agent's native hooks to Entire's event model.\\n\\n**Do NOT read other internal Entire source files** (`agent.go`, `event.go`, `hook_registry.go`, `lifecycle.go`, checklist, or reference implementations). The implementer handles those.\\n\\n### Phase 2: Static Capability Checks\\n\\nNon-destructive CLI probing. Record PASS/WARN/FAIL for each:\\n\\n| Check | Command | PASS | FAIL |\\n|-------|---------|------|------|\\n| Binary present | `command -v $AGENT_BIN` | Found | Not found (blocker) |\\n| Help output | `$AGENT_BIN --help` or `$AGENT_BIN help` | Available | No help |\\n| Version info | `$AGENT_BIN --version` or `$AGENT_BIN version` | Available | N/A |\\n| Hook keywords | Scan help for: hook, lifecycle, callback, event, trigger, pre-, post-, plugin, extension | Found | None found |\\n| Session keywords | Scan help for: session, resume, continue, history, transcript, context | Found | None found |\\n| Config directory | Check `~/.$AGENT_SLUG/`, `~/.config/$AGENT_SLUG/`, `./$AGENT_SLUG/`, `./.${AGENT_SLUG}/` | Found | None found |\\n| Documentation | Web search for hook/plugin/extension docs | Found | None found |\\n\\n### Phase 3: Test Script Creation\\n\\nBased on Phase 2 findings, create an **agent-specific** test script:\\n\\n```\\nscripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh\\n```\\n\\nThe script is tailored to the specific agent's hook mechanism (not a generic template). Adapt the hook wiring section based on what Phase 2 discovered.\\n\\n**Script structure:**\\n\\n```bash\\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\\nset -euo pipefail\\n\\nAGENT_NAME=\\\"...\\\"\\nAGENT_SLUG=\\\"...\\\"\\nAGENT_BIN=\\\"...\\\"\\nPROBE_DIR=\\\".entire/tmp/probe-${AGENT_SLUG}-$(date +%s)\\\"\\n```\\n\\n**Required sections:**\\n\\n1. **Static checks** — Re-runnable binary/version/help checks\\n2. **Hook wiring** — Create workspace-local config that intercepts hooks and dumps stdin JSON to `$PROBE_DIR/captures/<event-name>-<timestamp>.json`\\n3. **Run modes:**\\n   - `--run-cmd '<cmd>'` — Automated: launch agent, wait, collect\\n   - `--manual-live` — Interactive: user runs agent manually, presses Enter\\n4. **Capture collection** — List and pretty-print all payload files\\n5. **Cleanup** — Restore original config (unless `--keep-config`)\\n6. **Verdict** — PASS/WARN/FAIL per lifecycle event + COMPATIBLE/PARTIAL/INCOMPATIBLE\\n\\n### Phase 4: Execution & Analysis\\n\\nRun the script and analyze:\\n\\n1. **Execute**: `chmod +x scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh && scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh --manual-live`\\n2. **For each captured payload**: show command, artifact path, decoded JSON\\n3. **Lifecycle mapping**: native hook name → Entire EventType\\n4. **Field coverage**: which `Event` struct fields can be populated per event\\n\\n### Phase 5: Implementation One-Pager\\n\\nWrite the research findings to `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG/AGENT.md` as a structured one-pager that the test-writer and implementer phases will use as their single source of agent-specific information.\\n\\n**Create the agent package directory first** (if it doesn't exist):\\n\\n```bash\\nmkdir -p cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG\\n```\\n\\n**Write the one-pager using this template:**\\n\\n```markdown\\n# $AGENT_NAME — Integration One-Pager\\n\\n## Verdict: COMPATIBLE / PARTIAL / INCOMPATIBLE\\n\\n## Binary\\n- Name: `$AGENT_BIN`\\n- Version: ...\\n- Install: ... (how to install if not present)\\n\\n## Hook Mechanism\\n- Config file: `~/.config/$AGENT_SLUG/settings.json` (exact path)\\n- Config format: JSON / YAML / TOML\\n- Hook registration: ... (how hooks are declared — JSON objects, env vars, etc.)\\n- Hook names and when they fire:\\n  | Native Hook Name | When It Fires | Entire EventType |\\n  |-----------------|---------------|-----------------|\\n  | `on_session_start` | Agent session begins | `SessionStart` |\\n  | ... | ... | ... |\\n- Hook input (stdin JSON): ... (exact fields with example payload)\\n\\n## Transcript\\n- Location: `~/.config/$AGENT_SLUG/sessions/<id>/transcript.jsonl`\\n- Format: JSONL / JSON array / other\\n- Session ID extraction: ... (from hook payload field or directory name)\\n- Example entry: `{\\\"role\\\": \\\"user\\\", \\\"content\\\": \\\"...\\\"}`\\n\\n## Config Preservation\\n- Keys to preserve when modifying: ... (or \\\"use read-modify-write on entire file\\\")\\n- Settings that affect hook behavior: ...\\n\\n## CLI Flags\\n- Non-interactive prompt: `$AGENT_BIN --prompt \\\"...\\\" --no-confirm`\\n- Interactive mode: `$AGENT_BIN` (or \\\"not supported\\\")\\n- Relevant env vars: ...\\n\\n## Gaps & Limitations\\n- ... (anything that doesn't map cleanly)\\n\\n## Captured Payloads\\n- See `.entire/tmp/probe-$AGENT_SLUG-*/captures/` for raw JSON captures\\n```\\n\\n**Key points about the one-pager:**\\n\\n- The **Entire EventType mapping** (which native hook → which EventType) uses the event names learned from `agent-guide.md` in Phase 1. The researcher can do this mapping because it's a simple table — it doesn't need Entire source code.\\n- Fill in every section with concrete values from Phases 2-4. Don't leave placeholders.\\n- If a section doesn't apply (e.g., no transcript support), say so explicitly.\\n- This file persists as development documentation — future maintainers will reference it.\\n\\n## Blocker Handling\\n\\nIf blocked at any point (auth, sandbox, binary not found):\\n\\n1. State the exact blocker\\n2. Provide the exact command for the user to run manually\\n3. Explain what output to paste back\\n4. Continue with provided output\\n\\n## Constraints\\n\\n- **No Go code.** This command produces a one-pager and test script only.\\n- **Non-destructive.** All artifacts go under `.entire/tmp/` (gitignored). The one-pager goes in the agent package directory.\\n- **Agent-specific scripts.** Adapt based on Phase 2 findings, not